In this section, we propose a generative model for entity resolution that
incorporates a latent population of entities, each with a set of unknown
attributes.
Our model employs the Ewens-Pitman class of priors on the linkage structure
and a modified record distortion model that deviates from the common
â€œhit-missâ€ model used by Tancredi and Liseo (2011),
Steorts (2015) and Steorts etÂ al. (2016).
We provide an index of the modelâ€™s variables and an illustration of their
dependence structure in FigureÂ 2.
We close the section with a discussion of our modelâ€™s hyperparameters,
including recommendations about how to set these values when limited
prior information is available.

ER evaluation metrics are presented in TableÂ 2 for
the four linkage structure priors, assuming the rest of the model follows the
specification in SectionÂ 3.1.
Another perspective on ER accuracy is provided in
FigureÂ 3, which plots the relative error in the
inferred number of entities.
Both results demonstrate the benefit of placing hyperpriors on the
EPÂ parameters, as is done for PY, Ewens, and
GenCoupon.
These linkage structure priors achieve superior F1Â scores compared to
Coupon, where the EP parameters are fixed.
FigureÂ S8 (AppendixÂ D)
is consistent with this finding, demonstrating that vastly different values
of the EP parameters are inferred for each data set when hyperpriors are
used.
Another interesting observation is the fact that the ER accuracy is
relatively similar among PY, Ewens and GenCoupon.
This was unexpected at first, given the three parameter regimes are known
to exhibit distinct asymptotic behavior (see equation 1).
This suggests all three regimes may be flexible enough to model the
linkage structure of the data sets we consider here.
It would be interesting to see if these observations translate to much larger
data sets, where the asymptotic behavior of the three regimes would become
more apparent.

ER evaluation metrics are presented in TableÂ 3 for
all three models.
For simplicity we only provide results for our model under the
GenCoupon prior, which is denoted Ours in the table.
Our model achieves the highest (or equal-highest) F1Â score for all four
data sets.
We expect the poorer performance of blink is due to its use of
subjective (inflexible) priors and its distortion model, which tends to favour
high distortion and over-linkage.
Sadinle achieves the second highest F1Â score in the
non-private setting (RLdata, cora, rest),
and the lowest F1Â score in the private setting (nltcs).
The poorer performance for nltcs may be partly related to the
blocking scheme, which is less aggressive, leaving the model more susceptible
to over-linkage.
Another important factor is the sensitivity of Sadinle to the
truncation points for the priors on the mğ‘šm-probabilities.
We perform coarse-grained tuning of the truncation points in
AppendixÂ F, however fine-grained tuning could
result in additional performance gains.
